{"title_page": "John Spengler", "text_new": "'''John Daniel Spengler''' is an American health scholar currently serving as the [[Akira Yamaguchi]] Professor of Environmental Health and Human Habitation at [[Harvard T. H. Chan School of Public Health]] and a faculty member in the Harvard Department of Environmental Science and Public Policy and [[Harvard Faculty of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>[https://connects.catalyst.harvard.edu/Profiles/display/Person/63703 Harvard Catalyst profile for John Daniel Spengler, PhD]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/john-spengler/|title=John Spengler|publisher=harvard.edu|accessdate=May 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://environment.harvard.edu/about/faculty/john-spengler|title=John Spengler|publisher=harvard.edu|accessdate=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nSpengler earned a Bachelor of Science degree in physics from the [[University of Notre Dame]], a Master of Science in environmental health sciences from [[Harvard University]], Master of Science from the [[Harvard School of Public Health]], and PhD in Atmospheric Sciences from [[University at Albany, SUNY]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/john-spengler/|title=John Spengler|last=Boston|first=677 Huntington Avenue|last2=Ma 02115 +1495\u20111000|website=John Spengler|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.i2sl.org/conference/2006/abstracts/e2_spengler.htm|title=Labs21 2006 Conference Abstracts: E2|website=www.i2sl.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nSpengler has conducted research personal monitoring, the health effects of air and other environmental pollution, [[indoor air pollution]], and other [[environmental sustainability]] issues.\n\nHe chaired the committee on Harvard Sustainability Principles, served on Harvard's Greenhouse Gases Taskforce to develop the university's [[carbon reduction]] goals and strategies, and was a member of Harvard's Greenhouse Gases Executive Committee.\n\nHe has been an advisor to the [[World Health Organization]] on [[indoor air pollution]], personal exposure, and [[air pollution]] [[epidemiology]].\n\nIn 2003, Spengler received the 9th Annual [[Heinz Awards|Heinz Award]] for outstanding contributions to research related to the environment.\n\n== External references ==\n* [https://connects.catalyst.harvard.edu/Profiles/display/Person/63703 Harvard Catalyst profile for John Daniel Spengler, PhD]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spengler, John}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:American public health doctors]]\n[[Category:University at Albany, SUNY alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard School of Public Health alumni]]\n\n\n{{US-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''John Daniel Spengler''' is an American health scholar currently serving as the [[Akira Yamaguchi]] Professor of Environmental Health and Human Habitation at [[Harvard T. H. Chan School of Public Health]] and a Faculty member in the Harvard Department of Environmental Science and Public Policy and [[Harvard Faculty of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>[https://connects.catalyst.harvard.edu/Profiles/display/Person/63703 Harvard Catalyst profile for John Daniel Spengler, PhD]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/john-spengler/|title=John Spengler|publisher=harvard.edu|accessdate=May 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://environment.harvard.edu/about/faculty/john-spengler|title=John Spengler|publisher=harvard.edu|accessdate=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nSpengler earned a Bachelor of Science degree in Physics from the [[University of Notre Dame]], a Master of Science in environmental health sciences from [[Harvard University]], Master of Science from the [[Harvard School of Public Health]], and PhD in Atmospheric Sciences from [[University at Albany, SUNY]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/john-spengler/|title=John Spengler|last=Boston|first=677 Huntington Avenue|last2=Ma 02115 +1495\u20111000|website=John Spengler|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.i2sl.org/conference/2006/abstracts/e2_spengler.htm|title=Labs21 2006 Conference Abstracts: E2|website=www.i2sl.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nSpengler has conducted research personal monitoring, the health effects of air and other environmental pollution, [[indoor air pollution]], and other [[environmental sustainability]] issues.\n\nHe chaired the committee on Harvard Sustainability Principles, served on Harvard's Greenhouse Gases Taskforce to develop the University's [[carbon reduction]] goals and strategies, and was a member of Harvard's Greenhouse Gases Executive Committee.\n\nHe has been an advisor to the [[World Health Organization]] on [[indoor air pollution]], personal exposure, and [[air pollution]] [[epidemiology]].\n\nIn 2003, Spengler received the 9th Annual [[Heinz Awards|Heinz Award]] for outstanding contributions to research related to the environment.\n\n== External references ==\n* [https://connects.catalyst.harvard.edu/Profiles/display/Person/63703 Harvard Catalyst profile for John Daniel Spengler, PhD]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spengler, John}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:American public health doctors]]\n[[Category:University at Albany, SUNY alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard School of Public Health alumni]]\n\n\n{{US-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: Faculty \u2192 faculty, University \u2192 university, Physics \u2192 physics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Spengler"}
