{"title_page": "Sayaun Thunga Phulka", "text_new": "{{Infobox anthem\n|title = \u0938\u092f\u094c\u0902 \u0925\u0941\u0901\u0917\u093e \u092b\u0942\u0932\u0915\u093e\n|transcription = ''Saya\u0169 Th\u0169g\u0101 Ph\u016blk\u0101''\n|english_title I want a free game free day for me and my friends to buy a free free day game and buy a game and get a game that is a great free free day free free and game day for a game day for sure I can get a game that is great and free and great was a great was my first day of school Wow I want a puppy dog dog \n|image = Republic of nepal anthem notes.png\n|image_size = \n|caption =\n|prefix = National\n|country = {{NPL}}\n|author = [[Byakul Maila|By\u0101kul M\u0101il\u0101]]\n|lyrics_date =\n|composer = [[Amber Gurung]]\n|music_date =\n|adopted = 3 August 2006\n|until =\n|predecessor = ''[[Rastriya Gaan|R\u0101\u1e63\u1e6driya g\u0101n]]''\n|sound = Sayaun Thunga Phool Ka (instrumental).ogg\n|sound_title = ''Saya\u0169 Th\u0169g\u0101 Ph\u016blk\u0101'' (instrumental)\n}}\n'''''Saya\u0169 Th\u0169g\u0101 Ph\u016blk\u0101''''' ({{lang-ne|\u0938\u092f\u094c\u0902 \u0925\u0941\u0901\u0917\u093e \u092b\u0942\u0932\u0915\u093e}}, {{IPA-ne|s\u028cj\u028c\u0169 t\u02b0\u0169\u0261a p\u02b0ulka|pron}}; {{literal translation| 'Made of Hundreds of Flowers'}}) is the [[national anthem]] of [[Nepal]]. It was officially adopted as the  anthem on August 3, 2007, amid a ceremony held at the conference hall of National Planning Commission, inside the [[Singha Durbar]], by the speaker of the interim parliament, Mr. [[Subash Nemwang|Subash Chandra Nemwang]].<ref>[http://www.nepalnews.com.np/archive/2007/aug/aug03/news20.php Nepalnews.com Mercantile Communications Pvt. Ltd<!--Bot-generated title-->]</ref><ref>[http://www.kantipuronline.com/kolnews.php?nid=117987 eKantipur.com - Nepal's No.1 News Portal<!--Bot-generated title-->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927023024/http://www.kantipuronline.com/kolnews.php?nid=117987|date=2007-09-27}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hrnpKbqR0WM officially declared as the new Nepal national anthem on August 3, 2007]</ref> The previous Nepalese national anthem, \"[[Rastriya Gaan]]\", had been adopted in 1962, but it was dropped following the abolishment of the monarchy.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Republic_or_Death.html?id=GeasCAAAQBAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Republic or Death! Travels in Search of National Anthems|last=Marshall|first=Alex|publisher=Random House Books|year=2015|isbn=9781847947413|location=London|pages=33-63|quote=\"The Maoists...when they did finally agree peace, deciding to work within the political system after the public started protesting against the king in Kathmandu, one of their terms was that the anthem be changed.\"|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe lyrics of the National Anthem were penned by the poet Pradeep Kumar Rai, alias [[Byakul Maila]]. The music was composed by late [[Amber Gurung]]. The national anthem is simply worded, praising Nepali sovereignty, unity, courage, pride, scenic beauty, progress, peace, cultural and biological diversity, and respect. In August 2016, [[BBC]] ranked Nepal's national anthem third in its list of ''[[2016 Summer Olympics|Rio 2016]]: The most amazing national anthems'', citing its musical differences compared to other anthems.<ref name=\"Republica\">{{cite web|title=Nepal\u2019s national anthem third in \u2018The most amazing national anthems\u2019of world. list|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/3513|website=[[Republica]]|accessdate=10 August 2016|date=9 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Official lyrics in Nepali==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#000080\"|<div style=\"display:inline;color:#FFFFFF\">{{centre|'''Devanagari <small>(official)</small>'''}}</div>\n|bgcolor=\"#DC143C\"|<div style=\"display:inline;color:#FFFFFF\">{{centre|'''Romanisation'''}}</div>\n|bgcolor=\"#DC143C\"|<div style=\"display:inline;color:#FFFFFF\">{{centre|'''IPA transcription'''}}</div>\n|-\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 \u0938\u092f\u094c\u0902 \u0925\u0941\u0901\u0917\u093e \u092b\u0942\u0932\u0915\u093e \u0939\u093e\u092e\u0940, \u090f\u0909\u091f\u0948 \u092e\u093e\u0932\u093e \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940\n\u0938\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0935\u092d\u094c\u092e \u092d\u0908 \u092b\u0948\u0932\u093f\u090f\u0915\u093e, \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940-\u092e\u0939\u093e\u0915\u093e\u0932\u0940\u0964 \ud834\udd07\n\n\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0915\u0943\u0924\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0915\u094b\u091f\u0940-\u0915\u094b\u091f\u0940 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0926\u093e\u0915\u094b \u0906\u0902\u091a\u0932\n\u0935\u0940\u0930\u0939\u0930\u0942\u0915\u093e \u0930\u0917\u0924\u0932\u0947, \u0938\u094d\u0935\u0924\u0928\u094d\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0930 \u0905\u091f\u0932\u0964\n\n\u091c\u094d\u091e\u093e\u0928\u092d\u0942\u092e\u093f, \u0936\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u093f\u092d\u0942\u092e\u093f \u0924\u0930\u093e\u0908, \u092a\u0939\u093e\u0921, \u0939\u093f\u092e\u093e\u0932\n\u0905\u0916\u0923\u094d\u0921 \u092f\u094b \u092a\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094b \u0939\u093e\u092e\u094d\u0930\u094b \u092e\u093e\u0924\u0943\u092d\u0942\u092e\u093f \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0964\n\n\u092c\u0939\u0941 \u091c\u093e\u0924\u093f, \u092d\u093e\u0937\u093e, \u0927\u0930\u094d\u092e, \u0938\u0902\u0938\u094d\u0915\u0943\u0924\u093f \u091b\u0928\u094d \u0935\u093f\u0936\u093e\u0932\n\u0905\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0917\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u093e\u092e\u094d\u0930\u094b, \u091c\u092f \u091c\u092f \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0964<ref>[https://www.pariwartankhabar.com/2018/12/25/64874/ \u2018\u0935\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0915\u0941\u0932 \u092e\u093e\u0908\u0932\u093e\u2019 \u0915\u094b \u090f\u0909\u091f\u0948 \u092e\u093e\u0932\u093e\u092e\u093e \u0905\u091f\u093f\u090f\u0915\u093e \u0939\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/nepali/news/story/2007/08/printable/070803_national_anthem.shtml \u0917\u0941\u091e\u094d\u091c\u093f\u092f\u094b \u0928\u092f\u093e\u0901 \u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u0917\u093e\u0928 \u2013 BBCNepali.com, 2007]</ref><ref name=\"bad.org.uk\"/></poem>\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 Saya\u0169 th\u0169g\u0101 ph\u016blk\u0101 h\u0101m\u012b, eu\u1e6dai m\u0101l\u0101 nep\u0101l\u012b\nS\u0101rvabhaum bhai phailiek\u0101, Mec\u012b-Mah\u0101k\u0101l\u012b \ud834\udd07\n\nPrak\u1e5btik\u0101 ko\u1e6d\u012b-ko\u1e6d\u012b sampad\u0101ko \u0101\u0303cala,\nV\u012brhar\u016bk\u0101 ragatale, svatantra ra a\u1e6dala\n\nJ\u00f1\u0101nabh\u016bmi, \u015b\u0101ntibh\u016bmi Tarai, Pah\u0101\u1e0d, Him\u0101la\nAkha\u1e47\u1e0da yo py\u0101ro h\u0101mro m\u0101t\u1e5bbh\u016bmi Nep\u0101la\n\nBahul j\u0101ti, bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101, dharma, s\u00e3sk\u1e5bti chan vi\u015b\u0101la\nAgrag\u0101m\u012b r\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dra h\u0101mro, jaya jaya Nep\u0101la!</poem>\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 {{IPA|[s\u028cj\u028c\u0169 t\u02b0\u0169\u0261a p\u02b0ulka \u0266ami {{!}} eu\u0288\u028ci mala nepali]}}\n{{IPA|[sa\u027ev\u028cb\u02b1\u028cum b\u02b1\u028ci p\u02b0\u028cilieka {{!}} metsi-m\u028c\u0266akali]}} \ud834\udd07\n\n{{IPA|[p\u027e\u028ckr\u0325itika ko\u0288i-ko\u0288i s\u028cmp\u028cdako \u00e3ts\u028cl\u028c]}}\n{{IPA|[vi\u027e\u0266\u028c\u027euka \u027e\u028c\u0261\u028ct\u028cle sv\u028ct\u028cnt\u027e\u028c \u027e\u028c \u028c\u0288\u028cl\u028c]}}\n\n{{IPA|[dz\u0272an\u028cb\u02b1umi {{!}} \u0283antib\u02b1umi t\u028c\u027eai {{!}} p\u028c\u0266a\u0256 {{!}} \u0266imal\u028c]}}\n{{IPA|[\u028ck\u02b0\u028c\u0273\u0256\u028c jo p\u02b2a\u027eo \u0266am\u027eo matr\u0325ib\u02b1umi nepal\u028c]}}\n\n{{IPA|[b\u028c\u0266ul dzati {{!}} b\u02b1a\u0283a {{!}} d\u02b1\u028c\u027em\u028c {{!}} s\u00e3sk\u027eiti ts\u02b0\u028cn vi\u0283al\u028c]}}\n{{IPA|[\u028c\u0261\u027e\u028c\u0261ami \u027ea\u0283\u0288\u027e\u028c \u0266am\u027eo {{!}} dz\u028cj\u028c dz\u028cj\u028c nepal\u028c]}}<ref>The transcription is based on sources from [[Nepali phonology]] and [[Nepali language]]. See also [[Help:IPA/Nepali]].</ref></poem>\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=6\n!English translation<ref name=\"bad.org.uk\">[http://www.bad.org.uk/library-media/documents/DCOT%20Nepal%20Report%202019-Nav%20PAUL.pdf Dowling Club Overseas Trip Fellowship Report, Nepal (April 5-14th, 2019), By Dr. Nav Paul]</ref>\n!Singable English translation<ref>[http://www.nepaliclass.com/national-anthem-of-nepal-sayaun-thunga-phool-ka/ National Anthem of Nepal, Sayaun Thunga Phool Ka]</ref>\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 Woven from hundreds of flowers, we are [[Nepal|one garland that's Nepali]]\nSpread sovereign from [[Mechi]] to [[Mahakali Zone|Mahakali]]. \ud834\udd07\n\nA shawl of nature's wealth unending\nFrom the blood of the braves, a nation free and non-moving.\n\nA land of knowledge, of peace, the plains, hills and mountains tall\nIndivisible, this beloved land of ours, our motherland Nepal.\n\nOf many [[Demographics of Nepal|race]]s, languages, [[Religion in Nepal|religion]]s, and cultures of incredible sprawl\nThis progressive nation of ours, all hail Nepal!</poem>\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 Woven from hundred flowers, we are garland Nepali\nSovereignly extended from Mechi to Mahakali. \ud834\udd07\n\nMillions of natural beauties, history like a shawl\nBloods of the braves make it free and immotile.\n\nLand of peace, knowledge in the plains, hills and mountains\nOne-piece beloved country, motherland Nepal.\n\nRaces, languages, religions, cultures in-credible\nProgressive nation, I salute Nepal-aa!</poem>\n|}\n\n===Loose explanation===\nThe following explanation is meant for capturing the true essence of the national anthem:\n\n''\"We Nepalis, from different lingual, racial, religious or cultural background are the individual flower of a whole garland of the Nepali race. We have always been sovereign and we are spread out from our territories of Mechi to Mahakali.''\n\n''Blessed with Nature's millions gifts and blessed by the blood sacrificed by our Heroes, we are independent and are immovable - standing still with pride.''\n\n''Nepal - the land where knowledge shines, the peaceful nation consisting of Terai, Hills, and Mountains - is indivisible. It is our beloved motherland and we shall preserve its sovereignty at any cost.''\n\n''A melting pot of diverse races, numerous languages, and religions, Nepal is rich in its large diverse culture. We are a progressive people of the progressive nation and we don't look back - Jai Nepal!\"''\n\n== History ==\n\nAfter the unanimous decision on May 19, 2006, by the House of Representatives (''Pratinidhi Sabha'') of the Kingdom of Nepal, the old national anthem was suspended. On 30 November 2006, the National Anthem Selection Task Team (NASTT) selected poet [[Byakul Maila]]'s song as the new national anthem of Nepal. The new national anthem was selected from a total of 1272 submissions made from across the country. It was officially approved on 20 April 2007.<ref>[http://english.people.com.cn/200704/20/eng20070420_368365.html People's Daily Online - Nepali cabinet approves new national anthem<!--Bot-generated title-->]</ref>\n\nOn August 3, 2007, Sayaun Thunga Phool Ka was officially declared as Nepal's national anthem by the House of Representatives.\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn the screening process, Byakul Maila was required to prove he was not a royalist and encountered difficulties when it was discovered that he had once edited a book of poetry that contained a contribution from [[Gyanendra of Nepal|the king]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|last1=Marshall|first1=Alex|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-19063605|title=Olympics 2012: The secrets behind national anthems|date=1 August 2012|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nSome of Nepal's Maoist rulers prefer a stronger, more revolutionary anthem akin to the communist ''[[The Internationale|L'Internationale]],'' and even took their own CDs into the final selection meeting hoping to overturn Byakul Maila and Amber Gurung's effort.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Republic_or_Death.html?id=GeasCAAAQBAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Republic or Death! Travels in Search of National Anthems|last=Marshall|first=Alex|publisher=Random House Books|year=2015|isbn=9781847947413|location=London|pages=53|quote=\"I was asked to press play when one of the ministers brought out his own CD. He'd brought his own song to play. I couldn't believe it!\"|via=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Rastriya Gaan|R\u0101\u1e63\u1e6driya g\u0101n]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[BBC News]] has articles in [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6930099.stm English] and [http://www.bbc.co.uk/nepali/news/story/2007/08/070803_national_anthem.shtml Nepali] about the new anthem, with a full vocal recording in the latter version.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5_kMk-_Bt4g&list=PLNObRDITUjbHc5J6pmFluS8O1P3ypgh8F]\n\n{{National Anthems of Asia}}\n[[Category:National anthems]]\n[[Category:Nepalese songs]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Asian anthems]]\n[[Category:National anthem compositions in G minor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox anthem\n|title = \u0938\u092f\u094c\u0902 \u0925\u0941\u0901\u0917\u093e \u092b\u0942\u0932\u0915\u093e\n|transcription = ''Saya\u0169 Th\u0169g\u0101 Ph\u016blk\u0101''\n|english_title = 'Made of Hundreds of Flowers'\n|image = Republic of nepal anthem notes.png\n|image_size = \n|caption =\n|prefix = National\n|country = {{NPL}}\n|author = [[Byakul Maila|By\u0101kul M\u0101il\u0101]]\n|lyrics_date =\n|composer = [[Amber Gurung]]\n|music_date =\n|adopted = 3 August 2006\n|until =\n|predecessor = ''[[Rastriya Gaan|R\u0101\u1e63\u1e6driya g\u0101n]]''\n|sound = Sayaun Thunga Phool Ka (instrumental).ogg\n|sound_title = ''Saya\u0169 Th\u0169g\u0101 Ph\u016blk\u0101'' (instrumental)\n}}\n'''''Saya\u0169 Th\u0169g\u0101 Ph\u016blk\u0101''''' ({{lang-ne|\u0938\u092f\u094c\u0902 \u0925\u0941\u0901\u0917\u093e \u092b\u0942\u0932\u0915\u093e}}, {{IPA-ne|s\u028cj\u028c\u0169 t\u02b0\u0169\u0261a p\u02b0ulka|pron}}; {{literal translation| 'Made of Hundreds of Flowers'}}) is the [[national anthem]] of [[Nepal]]. It was officially adopted as the  anthem on August 3, 2007, amid a ceremony held at the conference hall of National Planning Commission, inside the [[Singha Durbar]], by the speaker of the interim parliament, Mr. [[Subash Nemwang|Subash Chandra Nemwang]].<ref>[http://www.nepalnews.com.np/archive/2007/aug/aug03/news20.php Nepalnews.com Mercantile Communications Pvt. Ltd<!--Bot-generated title-->]</ref><ref>[http://www.kantipuronline.com/kolnews.php?nid=117987 eKantipur.com - Nepal's No.1 News Portal<!--Bot-generated title-->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927023024/http://www.kantipuronline.com/kolnews.php?nid=117987|date=2007-09-27}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hrnpKbqR0WM officially declared as the new Nepal national anthem on August 3, 2007]</ref> The previous Nepalese national anthem, \"[[Rastriya Gaan]]\", had been adopted in 1962, but it was dropped following the abolishment of the monarchy.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Republic_or_Death.html?id=GeasCAAAQBAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Republic or Death! Travels in Search of National Anthems|last=Marshall|first=Alex|publisher=Random House Books|year=2015|isbn=9781847947413|location=London|pages=33-63|quote=\"The Maoists...when they did finally agree peace, deciding to work within the political system after the public started protesting against the king in Kathmandu, one of their terms was that the anthem be changed.\"|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe lyrics of the National Anthem were penned by the poet Pradeep Kumar Rai, alias [[Byakul Maila]]. The music was composed by late [[Amber Gurung]]. The national anthem is simply worded, praising Nepali sovereignty, unity, courage, pride, scenic beauty, progress, peace, cultural and biological diversity, and respect. In August 2016, [[BBC]] ranked Nepal's national anthem third in its list of ''[[2016 Summer Olympics|Rio 2016]]: The most amazing national anthems'', citing its musical differences compared to other anthems.<ref name=\"Republica\">{{cite web|title=Nepal\u2019s national anthem third in \u2018The most amazing national anthems\u2019of world. list|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/3513|website=[[Republica]]|accessdate=10 August 2016|date=9 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Official lyrics in Nepali==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#000080\"|<div style=\"display:inline;color:#FFFFFF\">{{centre|'''Devanagari <small>(official)</small>'''}}</div>\n|bgcolor=\"#DC143C\"|<div style=\"display:inline;color:#FFFFFF\">{{centre|'''Romanisation'''}}</div>\n|bgcolor=\"#DC143C\"|<div style=\"display:inline;color:#FFFFFF\">{{centre|'''IPA transcription'''}}</div>\n|-\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 \u0938\u092f\u094c\u0902 \u0925\u0941\u0901\u0917\u093e \u092b\u0942\u0932\u0915\u093e \u0939\u093e\u092e\u0940, \u090f\u0909\u091f\u0948 \u092e\u093e\u0932\u093e \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940\n\u0938\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0935\u092d\u094c\u092e \u092d\u0908 \u092b\u0948\u0932\u093f\u090f\u0915\u093e, \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940-\u092e\u0939\u093e\u0915\u093e\u0932\u0940\u0964 \ud834\udd07\n\n\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0915\u0943\u0924\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0915\u094b\u091f\u0940-\u0915\u094b\u091f\u0940 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0926\u093e\u0915\u094b \u0906\u0902\u091a\u0932\n\u0935\u0940\u0930\u0939\u0930\u0942\u0915\u093e \u0930\u0917\u0924\u0932\u0947, \u0938\u094d\u0935\u0924\u0928\u094d\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0930 \u0905\u091f\u0932\u0964\n\n\u091c\u094d\u091e\u093e\u0928\u092d\u0942\u092e\u093f, \u0936\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u093f\u092d\u0942\u092e\u093f \u0924\u0930\u093e\u0908, \u092a\u0939\u093e\u0921, \u0939\u093f\u092e\u093e\u0932\n\u0905\u0916\u0923\u094d\u0921 \u092f\u094b \u092a\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094b \u0939\u093e\u092e\u094d\u0930\u094b \u092e\u093e\u0924\u0943\u092d\u0942\u092e\u093f \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0964\n\n\u092c\u0939\u0941 \u091c\u093e\u0924\u093f, \u092d\u093e\u0937\u093e, \u0927\u0930\u094d\u092e, \u0938\u0902\u0938\u094d\u0915\u0943\u0924\u093f \u091b\u0928\u094d \u0935\u093f\u0936\u093e\u0932\n\u0905\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0917\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u093e\u092e\u094d\u0930\u094b, \u091c\u092f \u091c\u092f \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0964<ref>[https://www.pariwartankhabar.com/2018/12/25/64874/ \u2018\u0935\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0915\u0941\u0932 \u092e\u093e\u0908\u0932\u093e\u2019 \u0915\u094b \u090f\u0909\u091f\u0948 \u092e\u093e\u0932\u093e\u092e\u093e \u0905\u091f\u093f\u090f\u0915\u093e \u0939\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/nepali/news/story/2007/08/printable/070803_national_anthem.shtml \u0917\u0941\u091e\u094d\u091c\u093f\u092f\u094b \u0928\u092f\u093e\u0901 \u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u0917\u093e\u0928 \u2013 BBCNepali.com, 2007]</ref><ref name=\"bad.org.uk\"/></poem>\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 Saya\u0169 th\u0169g\u0101 ph\u016blk\u0101 h\u0101m\u012b, eu\u1e6dai m\u0101l\u0101 nep\u0101l\u012b\nS\u0101rvabhaum bhai phailiek\u0101, Mec\u012b-Mah\u0101k\u0101l\u012b \ud834\udd07\n\nPrak\u1e5btik\u0101 ko\u1e6d\u012b-ko\u1e6d\u012b sampad\u0101ko \u0101\u0303cala,\nV\u012brhar\u016bk\u0101 ragatale, svatantra ra a\u1e6dala\n\nJ\u00f1\u0101nabh\u016bmi, \u015b\u0101ntibh\u016bmi Tarai, Pah\u0101\u1e0d, Him\u0101la\nAkha\u1e47\u1e0da yo py\u0101ro h\u0101mro m\u0101t\u1e5bbh\u016bmi Nep\u0101la\n\nBahul j\u0101ti, bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101, dharma, s\u00e3sk\u1e5bti chan vi\u015b\u0101la\nAgrag\u0101m\u012b r\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dra h\u0101mro, jaya jaya Nep\u0101la!</poem>\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 {{IPA|[s\u028cj\u028c\u0169 t\u02b0\u0169\u0261a p\u02b0ulka \u0266ami {{!}} eu\u0288\u028ci mala nepali]}}\n{{IPA|[sa\u027ev\u028cb\u02b1\u028cum b\u02b1\u028ci p\u02b0\u028cilieka {{!}} metsi-m\u028c\u0266akali]}} \ud834\udd07\n\n{{IPA|[p\u027e\u028ckr\u0325itika ko\u0288i-ko\u0288i s\u028cmp\u028cdako \u00e3ts\u028cl\u028c]}}\n{{IPA|[vi\u027e\u0266\u028c\u027euka \u027e\u028c\u0261\u028ct\u028cle sv\u028ct\u028cnt\u027e\u028c \u027e\u028c \u028c\u0288\u028cl\u028c]}}\n\n{{IPA|[dz\u0272an\u028cb\u02b1umi {{!}} \u0283antib\u02b1umi t\u028c\u027eai {{!}} p\u028c\u0266a\u0256 {{!}} \u0266imal\u028c]}}\n{{IPA|[\u028ck\u02b0\u028c\u0273\u0256\u028c jo p\u02b2a\u027eo \u0266am\u027eo matr\u0325ib\u02b1umi nepal\u028c]}}\n\n{{IPA|[b\u028c\u0266ul dzati {{!}} b\u02b1a\u0283a {{!}} d\u02b1\u028c\u027em\u028c {{!}} s\u00e3sk\u027eiti ts\u02b0\u028cn vi\u0283al\u028c]}}\n{{IPA|[\u028c\u0261\u027e\u028c\u0261ami \u027ea\u0283\u0288\u027e\u028c \u0266am\u027eo {{!}} dz\u028cj\u028c dz\u028cj\u028c nepal\u028c]}}<ref>The transcription is based on sources from [[Nepali phonology]] and [[Nepali language]]. See also [[Help:IPA/Nepali]].</ref></poem>\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=6\n!English translation<ref name=\"bad.org.uk\">[http://www.bad.org.uk/library-media/documents/DCOT%20Nepal%20Report%202019-Nav%20PAUL.pdf Dowling Club Overseas Trip Fellowship Report, Nepal (April 5-14th, 2019), By Dr. Nav Paul]</ref>\n!Singable English translation<ref>[http://www.nepaliclass.com/national-anthem-of-nepal-sayaun-thunga-phool-ka/ National Anthem of Nepal, Sayaun Thunga Phool Ka]</ref>\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 Woven from hundreds of flowers, we are [[Nepal|one garland that's Nepali]]\nSpread sovereign from [[Mechi]] to [[Mahakali Zone|Mahakali]]. \ud834\udd07\n\nA shawl of nature's wealth unending\nFrom the blood of the braves, a nation free and non-moving.\n\nA land of knowledge, of peace, the plains, hills and mountains tall\nIndivisible, this beloved land of ours, our motherland Nepal.\n\nOf many [[Demographics of Nepal|race]]s, languages, [[Religion in Nepal|religion]]s, and cultures of incredible sprawl\nThis progressive nation of ours, all hail Nepal!</poem>\n|<poem>\ud834\udd06 Woven from hundred flowers, we are garland Nepali\nSovereignly extended from Mechi to Mahakali. \ud834\udd07\n\nMillions of natural beauties, history like a shawl\nBloods of the braves make it free and immotile.\n\nLand of peace, knowledge in the plains, hills and mountains\nOne-piece beloved country, motherland Nepal.\n\nRaces, languages, religions, cultures in-credible\nProgressive nation, I salute Nepal-aa!</poem>\n|}\n\n===Loose explanation===\nThe following explanation is meant for capturing the true essence of the national anthem:\n\n''\"We Nepalis, from different lingual, racial, religious or cultural background are the individual flower of a whole garland of the Nepali race. We have always been sovereign and we are spread out from our territories of Mechi to Mahakali.''\n\n''Blessed with Nature's millions gifts and blessed by the blood sacrificed by our Heroes, we are independent and are immovable - standing still with pride.''\n\n''Nepal - the land where knowledge shines, the peaceful nation consisting of Terai, Hills, and Mountains - is indivisible. It is our beloved motherland and we shall preserve its sovereignty at any cost.''\n\n''A melting pot of diverse races, numerous languages, and religions, Nepal is rich in its large diverse culture. We are a progressive people of the progressive nation and we don't look back - Jai Nepal!\"''\n\n== History ==\n\nAfter the unanimous decision on May 19, 2006, by the House of Representatives (''Pratinidhi Sabha'') of the Kingdom of Nepal, the old national anthem was suspended. On 30 November 2006, the National Anthem Selection Task Team (NASTT) selected poet [[Byakul Maila]]'s song as the new national anthem of Nepal. The new national anthem was selected from a total of 1272 submissions made from across the country. It was officially approved on 20 April 2007.<ref>[http://english.people.com.cn/200704/20/eng20070420_368365.html People's Daily Online - Nepali cabinet approves new national anthem<!--Bot-generated title-->]</ref>\n\nOn August 3, 2007, Sayaun Thunga Phool Ka was officially declared as Nepal's national anthem by the House of Representatives.\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn the screening process, Byakul Maila was required to prove he was not a royalist and encountered difficulties when it was discovered that he had once edited a book of poetry that contained a contribution from [[Gyanendra of Nepal|the king]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|last1=Marshall|first1=Alex|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-19063605|title=Olympics 2012: The secrets behind national anthems|date=1 August 2012|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nSome of Nepal's Maoist rulers prefer a stronger, more revolutionary anthem akin to the communist ''[[The Internationale|L'Internationale]],'' and even took their own CDs into the final selection meeting hoping to overturn Byakul Maila and Amber Gurung's effort.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Republic_or_Death.html?id=GeasCAAAQBAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Republic or Death! Travels in Search of National Anthems|last=Marshall|first=Alex|publisher=Random House Books|year=2015|isbn=9781847947413|location=London|pages=53|quote=\"I was asked to press play when one of the ministers brought out his own CD. He'd brought his own song to play. I couldn't believe it!\"|via=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Rastriya Gaan|R\u0101\u1e63\u1e6driya g\u0101n]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[BBC News]] has articles in [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6930099.stm English] and [http://www.bbc.co.uk/nepali/news/story/2007/08/070803_national_anthem.shtml Nepali] about the new anthem, with a full vocal recording in the latter version.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5_kMk-_Bt4g&list=PLNObRDITUjbHc5J6pmFluS8O1P3ypgh8F]\n\n{{National Anthems of Asia}}\n[[Category:National anthems]]\n[[Category:Nepalese songs]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Asian anthems]]\n[[Category:National anthem compositions in G minor]]\n", "name_user": "98.11.228.159", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sayaun_Thunga_Phulka"}
